[
  {
    "id": 2,
    "chapter": "I. The Twin-Verses",
    "themes": ["mindfulness", "thoughts", "hope", "peace", "self-awareness"],
    "text": {
      "en": "All that we are arises from our thoughts; we are made of our thoughts. Speak or act with a clear mind, and happiness follows like a shadow that never leaves.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 2",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 4,
    "chapter": "I. The Twin-Verses",
    "themes": ["anger", "resentment", "forgiveness", "letting-go", "healing"],
    "text": {
      "en": "\"He wronged me, he hurt me, he failed me.\" In those who let go of such thoughts, resentment finds its end.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 4",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 5,
    "chapter": "I. The Twin-Verses",
    "themes": ["anger", "resentment", "forgiveness", "conflict", "relationships"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Hatred is never ended by hatred. Hatred ends only through love. This is an ancient and unchanging truth.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 5",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 8,
    "chapter": "I. The Twin-Verses",
    "themes": ["inner-strength", "temptation", "stability", "discipline", "resilience"],
    "text": {
      "en": "One who lives with senses calmed, moderate, faithful, and strong, temptation cannot overthrow, any more than the wind can topple a mountain of rock.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 8",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 14,
    "chapter": "I. The Twin-Verses",
    "themes": ["peace", "restless-mind", "reflection", "stability", "protection"],
    "text": {
      "en": "As rain cannot break through a well-thatched roof, desire cannot break through a mind that is calm and well-reflecting.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 14",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 16,
    "chapter": "I. The Twin-Verses",
    "themes": ["hope", "encouragement", "virtue", "peace", "self-worth"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The one who does good rejoices here and rejoices beyond. Seeing the goodness of their own deeds, they delight and find peace.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 16",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 23,
    "chapter": "II. On Earnestness",
    "themes": ["peace", "meditation", "perseverance", "inner-strength", "stillness"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The wise, steady and ever meditative, reach a peace beyond all bonds — the highest happiness.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 23",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 24,
    "chapter": "II. On Earnestness",
    "themes": ["effort", "growth", "discipline", "encouragement", "self-improvement"],
    "text": {
      "en": "If one is earnest and mindful, pure in deed and considerate, restrained and living rightly, their well-being steadily grows.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 24",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 25,
    "chapter": "II. On Earnestness",
    "themes": ["anxiety", "overwhelm", "resilience", "discipline", "inner-strength"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Through effort, attentiveness, and self-restraint, the wise build within themselves an island that no flood can ever wash away.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 25",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 28,
    "chapter": "II. On Earnestness",
    "themes": ["clarity", "perspective", "wisdom", "calm", "rising-above"],
    "text": {
      "en": "When the wise dispel carelessness with care, they climb the high tower of wisdom and look out, sorrowless, upon the sorrowing crowd below.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 28",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 33,
    "chapter": "III. Thought",
    "themes": ["restless-mind", "overthinking", "focus", "self-discipline", "anxiety"],
    "text": {
      "en": "As an arrow-maker straightens his arrow, the wise steady their trembling, restless thoughts, so hard to guard, so hard to hold.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 33",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 35,
    "chapter": "III. Thought",
    "themes": ["anxiety", "restless-mind", "overthinking", "peace", "meditation"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The mind is restless and hard to restrain, rushing wherever it wishes. To gentle it is good, for a settled mind brings peace.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 35",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 36,
    "chapter": "III. Thought",
    "themes": ["mindfulness", "self-awareness", "peace", "focus", "protection"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The mind is subtle and hard to see, drawn wherever it desires. Let the wise watch over it, for a guarded mind brings happiness.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 36",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 39,
    "chapter": "III. Thought",
    "themes": ["peace", "fearlessness", "clarity", "letting-go", "calm"],
    "text": {
      "en": "One whose mind is untroubled, whose thoughts are not scattered, who has set aside both good and ill — for the watchful, there is no fear.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 39",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 43,
    "chapter": "III. Thought",
    "themes": ["self-compassion", "mindset", "healing", "relationships", "inner-strength"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Not a mother, not a father, nor any relative can do you as much good as your own well-directed mind.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 43",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 49,
    "chapter": "IV. Flowers",
    "themes": ["gentleness", "living-lightly", "non-harm", "balance", "grace"],
    "text": {
      "en": "As a bee gathers nectar and leaves the flower unharmed, its colour and fragrance untouched, so let the wise move through the world.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 49",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 50,
    "chapter": "IV. Flowers",
    "themes": ["comparison", "judgment", "self-focus", "letting-go", "relationships"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Do not dwell on the faults of others, on what they have done or failed to do. Look instead to your own actions, to what you have done and left undone.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 50",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 51,
    "chapter": "IV. Flowers",
    "themes": ["integrity", "action", "authenticity", "words-and-deeds", "growth"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Like a lovely flower full of colour but without scent are the fine words of one who does not act on them.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 51",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 53,
    "chapter": "IV. Flowers",
    "themes": ["purpose", "hope", "opportunity", "making-the-most", "encouragement"],
    "text": {
      "en": "As many garlands can be woven from a heap of flowers, so much good can be made by one born into this life.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 53",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 54,
    "chapter": "IV. Flowers",
    "themes": ["character", "integrity", "reputation", "goodness", "quiet-influence"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The scent of flowers cannot travel against the wind, but the fragrance of a good person travels even against it; goodness reaches everywhere.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 54",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 61,
    "chapter": "V. The Fool",
    "themes": ["solitude", "relationships", "self-respect", "independence", "boundaries"],
    "text": {
      "en": "If on your journey you find no equal or better companion, walk on alone with resolve; there is no true company with the foolish.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 61",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 62,
    "chapter": "V. The Fool",
    "themes": ["attachment", "possessions", "anxiety", "letting-go", "impermanence"],
    "text": {
      "en": "\"These are mine, this wealth is mine\" — such thoughts torment the unwise. You do not even belong to yourself; how then can sons or wealth?",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 62",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 63,
    "chapter": "V. The Fool",
    "themes": ["humility", "self-awareness", "wisdom", "growth", "honesty"],
    "text": {
      "en": "A fool who knows their foolishness is wise at least in that. But a fool who thinks themselves wise is a fool indeed.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 63",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 80,
    "chapter": "VI. The Wise Man",
    "themes": ["self-mastery", "growth", "self-improvement", "discipline", "shaping-oneself"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Those who guide water channel it; arrow-makers shape the arrow; carpenters shape the wood; the wise shape themselves.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 80",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 81,
    "chapter": "VI. The Wise Man",
    "themes": ["criticism", "praise", "stability", "equanimity", "inner-strength"],
    "text": {
      "en": "As a great rock stands unmoved by the wind, the wise are not shaken by blame or by praise.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 81",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 82,
    "chapter": "VI. The Wise Man",
    "themes": ["peace", "calm", "serenity", "wisdom", "stillness"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Having heard the teachings, the wise grow serene, like a lake deep, clear, and still.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 82",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 83,
    "chapter": "VI. The Wise Man",
    "themes": ["equanimity", "acceptance", "emotional-balance", "resilience", "calm"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The good walk on through whatever comes. Touched by joy or by sorrow, the wise show neither elation nor despair.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 83",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 90,
    "chapter": "VII. The Venerable",
    "themes": ["grief", "letting-go", "freedom", "healing", "peace"],
    "text": {
      "en": "For the one who has completed the journey, released sorrow, and let go of every bond, there is no more suffering.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 90",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 96,
    "chapter": "VII. The Venerable",
    "themes": ["peace", "calm", "serenity", "stillness", "contentment"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Quiet is their mind, quiet their speech and action, for those who have found freedom through true understanding and become still.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 96",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 103,
    "chapter": "VIII. The Thousands",
    "themes": ["self-mastery", "inner-strength", "discipline", "growth"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Though one may conquer a thousand times a thousand in battle, the greatest victor is the one who conquers himself.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 103",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 111,
    "chapter": "VIII. The Thousands",
    "themes": ["wisdom", "presence", "quality-of-life", "meaning", "mindfulness"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Better than a hundred years lived in ignorance and unrest is a single day lived wisely and with reflection.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 111",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 112,
    "chapter": "VIII. The Thousands",
    "themes": ["perseverance", "strength", "resilience", "effort", "meaning"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Better than a hundred years lived idle and weak is a single day lived with firm and steady strength.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 112",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 116,
    "chapter": "IX. Evil",
    "themes": ["good-habits", "procrastination", "encouragement", "action", "growth"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Be quick to do good, and hold your mind back from harm. When one is slow to do good, the mind takes delight in wrong.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 116",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 118,
    "chapter": "IX. Evil",
    "themes": ["good-habits", "encouragement", "hope", "growth", "positivity"],
    "text": {
      "en": "If you do good, do it again and again; take delight in it. The gathering of good brings happiness.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 118",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 121,
    "chapter": "IX. Evil",
    "themes": ["habits", "small-steps", "responsibility", "patience"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Do not take small wrongs lightly, thinking they will not reach you. Drop by drop a pot is filled; little by little, harm gathers within.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 121",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 122,
    "chapter": "IX. Evil",
    "themes": ["small-steps", "habits", "hope", "growth", "encouragement"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Do not take small goodness lightly, thinking it will not reach you. Drop by drop a pot is filled; little by little, the wise become full of good.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 122",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 145,
    "chapter": "X. Punishment",
    "themes": ["self-improvement", "growth", "discipline", "responsibility"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Those who channel water guide it where they will; the arrow-maker shapes the arrow; the carpenter shapes the wood. In the same way, the good shape themselves.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 145",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 146,
    "chapter": "XI. Old Age",
    "themes": ["seeking", "hope", "darkness", "awakening", "anxiety"],
    "text": {
      "en": "How can there be laughter, how can there be joy, when the world is forever burning? Surrounded by darkness, why do you not seek the light?",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 146",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 160,
    "chapter": "XII. Self",
    "themes": ["self-reliance", "responsibility", "inner-strength", "growth"],
    "text": {
      "en": "You are your own refuge; who else could be? When you have truly mastered yourself, you find a refuge rare and hard to gain.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 160",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 165,
    "chapter": "XII. Self",
    "themes": ["responsibility", "self-focus", "growth", "letting-go", "self-doubt"],
    "text": {
      "en": "By yourself wrong is done; by yourself you suffer. By yourself wrong is left undone; by yourself you are made pure. Purity and impurity are your own; no one can purify another.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 165",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 166,
    "chapter": "XII. Self",
    "themes": ["self-care", "priorities", "boundaries", "duty", "self-respect"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Do not neglect your own path for another's, however great. Having clearly seen what is yours to do, attend to it fully.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 166",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 172,
    "chapter": "XIII. The World",
    "themes": ["redemption", "second-chances", "hope", "change", "forgiveness"],
    "text": {
      "en": "One who was once careless and later grows mindful lights up the world, like the moon emerging from behind the clouds.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 172",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 183,
    "chapter": "XIV. The Buddha",
    "themes": ["simplicity", "purpose", "guidance", "clarity", "living-well"],
    "text": {
      "en": "To do no harm, to cultivate good, and to purify the mind — this is the heart of the teaching.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 183",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 184,
    "chapter": "XIV. The Buddha",
    "themes": ["patience", "endurance", "peace", "conflict", "forbearance"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Patient endurance is the highest discipline. Those who harm or insult others have not yet found the way.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 184",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 197,
    "chapter": "XV. Happiness",
    "themes": ["peace", "forgiveness", "relationships", "letting-go", "equanimity"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Let us live in joy, free from hatred among those who hate. Among people who hate, let us dwell without hatred.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 197",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 200,
    "chapter": "XV. Happiness",
    "themes": ["contentment", "simplicity", "gratitude", "freedom", "joy"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Let us live in joy, though we call nothing our own. Like the radiant gods, let us feed on happiness itself.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 200",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 201,
    "chapter": "XV. Happiness",
    "themes": ["letting-go", "peace", "conflict", "contentment", "ego"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Victory breeds hatred, and the defeated sleep in pain. Letting go of both victory and defeat, the peaceful rest in happiness.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 201",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 204,
    "chapter": "XV. Happiness",
    "themes": ["gratitude", "contentment", "health", "trust", "perspective"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Health is the greatest gift, contentment the greatest wealth, trust the finest kinship, and peace the highest joy.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 204",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 205,
    "chapter": "XV. Happiness",
    "themes": ["solitude", "peace", "fearlessness", "calm", "self-sufficiency"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Having tasted the sweetness of solitude and stillness, one becomes free of fear and free of wrong.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 205",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 212,
    "chapter": "XVI. Pleasure",
    "themes": ["attachment", "fear", "grief", "letting-go", "freedom"],
    "text": {
      "en": "From clinging comes grief, from clinging comes fear. For one who is free from clinging, there is no grief — and where is fear?",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 212",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 6,
    "chapter": "I. The Twin-Verses",
    "themes": ["conflict", "perspective", "letting-go", "mortality", "peace"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Most never see that we all must end one day. For those who truly see this, their quarrels fall away.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 6",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 18,
    "chapter": "I. The Twin-Verses",
    "themes": ["hope", "self-worth", "encouragement", "positivity", "peace"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The one who does good is glad in this world and the next. Looking back on their own good deeds, they are glad, and walk on gladder still.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 18",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 26,
    "chapter": "II. On Earnestness",
    "themes": ["focus", "priorities", "wisdom", "mindfulness", "values"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The careless chase after empty things; the wise guard their attentiveness as their most precious treasure.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 26",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 27,
    "chapter": "II. On Earnestness",
    "themes": ["focus", "joy", "meditation", "presence", "contentment"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Do not lose yourself in distraction or fleeting pleasure. The one who is attentive and reflective finds abundant joy.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 27",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 29,
    "chapter": "II. On Earnestness",
    "themes": ["perseverance", "growth", "focus", "progress", "encouragement"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Attentive among the heedless, awake among the sleeping, the wise move forward like a swift horse leaving a weaker one behind.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 29",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 84,
    "chapter": "VI. The Wise Man",
    "themes": ["integrity", "ambition", "honesty", "values", "contentment"],
    "text": {
      "en": "One who seeks neither wealth nor status by unfair means, and not even success at another's cost — that one is good, wise, and true.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 84",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 89,
    "chapter": "VI. The Wise Man",
    "themes": ["freedom", "letting-go", "peace", "clarity", "liberation"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Those who cling to nothing and rejoice in freedom from attachment, whose minds are bright and clear, are free even in this very life.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 89",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 95,
    "chapter": "VII. The Venerable",
    "themes": ["patience", "equanimity", "calm", "resilience", "tolerance"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Patient like the earth, steady as a threshold, clear as a lake without mud — such is the one who has found peace.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 95",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 100,
    "chapter": "VIII. The Thousands",
    "themes": ["simplicity", "clarity", "meaning", "words", "wisdom"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Better than a thousand hollow words is one word of meaning, which brings the listener peace.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 100",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 102,
    "chapter": "VIII. The Thousands",
    "themes": ["meaning", "focus", "wisdom", "simplicity", "peace"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Better than a hundred empty verses is a single line of truth, which brings the listener peace.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 102",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 117,
    "chapter": "IX. Evil",
    "themes": ["mistakes", "change", "self-forgiveness", "growth", "letting-go"],
    "text": {
      "en": "If you have done wrong, do not repeat it, and do not take delight in it. The piling up of harm brings only pain.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 117",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 120,
    "chapter": "IX. Evil",
    "themes": ["patience", "hope", "trust", "timing", "perseverance"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Even the good may meet hard days before their good unfolds. But when it ripens, the good see brighter days.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 120",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 159,
    "chapter": "XII. Self",
    "themes": ["integrity", "authenticity", "leading-by-example", "self-discipline", "growth"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Become first what you would teach others to be. Hard it is to master oneself; master that, and you may help others.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 159",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 168,
    "chapter": "XIII. The World",
    "themes": ["motivation", "action", "encouragement", "new-start", "effort"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Rouse yourself! Do not be idle. Follow the path of good, and you will rest in peace, in this world and beyond.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 168",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 170,
    "chapter": "XIII. The World",
    "themes": ["impermanence", "perspective", "letting-go", "detachment", "calm"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Look upon the world as a bubble, look upon it as a mirage. The one who sees it so is not seized by fear.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 170",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 173,
    "chapter": "XIII. The World",
    "themes": ["redemption", "second-chances", "hope", "change", "forgiveness"],
    "text": {
      "en": "One whose past wrongs are covered over by good lights up the world, like the moon emerging from behind the clouds.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 173",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 178,
    "chapter": "XIII. The World",
    "themes": ["values", "inner-wealth", "priorities", "meaning", "growth"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Greater than rule over the earth, greater than the heavens, is the first step taken on the path of awakening.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 178",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 185,
    "chapter": "XIV. The Buddha",
    "themes": ["restraint", "peace", "simplicity", "kindness", "living-well"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Speak no blame, do no harm, live with restraint, be moderate, and dwell on what is highest — this is the heart of the teaching.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 185",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 198,
    "chapter": "XV. Happiness",
    "themes": ["peace", "wellbeing", "resilience", "equanimity", "calm"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Let us live in joy, in good health among the ailing. Among those who are unwell, let us dwell at ease.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 198",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 202,
    "chapter": "XV. Happiness",
    "themes": ["peace", "desire", "rest", "contentment", "calm"],
    "text": {
      "en": "There is no fire like craving, no grip like hatred. There is no peace higher than rest.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 202",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 207,
    "chapter": "XV. Happiness",
    "themes": ["relationships", "company", "boundaries", "wisdom", "belonging"],
    "text": {
      "en": "To walk with the foolish brings long sorrow. But company with the wise is joy, like meeting one's own family.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 207",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 213,
    "chapter": "XVI. Pleasure",
    "themes": ["grief", "attachment", "fear", "love", "letting-go"],
    "text": {
      "en": "From affection comes grief, from affection comes fear. For one free from the grip of affection, there is no grief — and where is fear?",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 213",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 216,
    "chapter": "XVI. Pleasure",
    "themes": ["worry", "money", "anxiety", "letting-go", "freedom"],
    "text": {
      "en": "From craving comes grief, from craving comes fear. For one free from craving, there is no grief — and where is fear?",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 216",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 219,
    "chapter": "XVI. Pleasure",
    "themes": ["homecoming", "belonging", "relationships", "reunion", "comfort"],
    "text": {
      "en": "As family and friends welcome home one long away and safely returned,",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 219",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 220,
    "chapter": "XVI. Pleasure",
    "themes": ["legacy", "goodness", "comfort", "reassurance", "meaning"],
    "text": {
      "en": "so one's own good deeds welcome the doer who has lived well — as kinsfolk welcome a dear one returning home.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 220",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 221,
    "chapter": "XVII. Anger",
    "themes": ["anger", "pride", "letting-go", "freedom", "peace"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Let go of anger, set aside pride, and slip free of every binding. Suffering does not cling to the one who clings to nothing.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 221",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 222,
    "chapter": "XVII. Anger",
    "themes": ["anger", "self-control", "strength", "restraint", "emotional-balance"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The one who holds back rising anger as a driver reins a runaway chariot — that one I call a true charioteer; the rest merely hold the reins.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 222",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 223,
    "chapter": "XVII. Anger",
    "themes": ["anger", "kindness", "conflict", "generosity", "truth"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Conquer anger with love, wrong with good, the stingy with giving, and the liar with truth.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 223",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 227,
    "chapter": "XVII. Anger",
    "themes": ["criticism", "judgment", "acceptance", "perspective", "resilience"],
    "text": {
      "en": "This is an old truth, not new: they blame the silent, they blame the talkative, they blame the moderate. No one on earth escapes blame.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 227",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 228,
    "chapter": "XVII. Anger",
    "themes": ["criticism", "praise", "acceptance", "perspective", "equanimity"],
    "text": {
      "en": "There never was, and never will be, nor is there now, anyone who is only blamed or only praised.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 228",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 234,
    "chapter": "XVII. Anger",
    "themes": ["self-control", "mindfulness", "emotional-balance", "discipline", "peace"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The wise who are restrained in body, in speech, and in mind — they are well restrained indeed.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 234",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 239,
    "chapter": "XVIII. Impurity",
    "themes": ["small-steps", "self-improvement", "patience", "growth", "persistence"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Little by little, moment by moment, let the wise clear away their own flaws, as a smith refines silver.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 239",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 249,
    "chapter": "XVIII. Impurity",
    "themes": ["envy", "comparison", "restlessness", "peace", "contentment"],
    "text": {
      "en": "One who frets and envies what others are given finds no rest, by day or by night.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 249",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 250,
    "chapter": "XVIII. Impurity",
    "themes": ["peace", "contentment", "letting-go", "envy", "calm"],
    "text": {
      "en": "But one in whom that envy is uprooted entirely finds rest, by day and by night.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 250",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 252,
    "chapter": "XVIII. Impurity",
    "themes": ["self-awareness", "judgment", "humility", "perspective", "honesty"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The faults of others are easy to see; our own are hard. We winnow others' faults like chaff, but hide our own.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 252",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 258,
    "chapter": "XIX. The Just",
    "themes": ["wisdom", "patience", "fearlessness", "character", "calm"],
    "text": {
      "en": "One is not wise merely by speaking much. The patient, free from hatred and fear — that one is truly wise.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 258",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 276,
    "chapter": "XX. The Way",
    "themes": ["self-effort", "responsibility", "empowerment", "action", "growth"],
    "text": {
      "en": "You yourself must walk the path; the awakened only point the way. Those who set out, meditative, are freed from bondage.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 276",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 277,
    "chapter": "XX. The Way",
    "themes": ["impermanence", "acceptance", "letting-go", "perspective", "peace"],
    "text": {
      "en": "\"All things made must pass.\" Seeing this clearly, one grows calm in the midst of pain — this is the path to peace.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 277",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 280,
    "chapter": "XX. The Way",
    "themes": ["procrastination", "motivation", "effort", "discipline", "action"],
    "text": {
      "en": "One who will not rise when it is time to rise, who is young and strong yet idle and weak in resolve, will never find the way of wisdom.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 280",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 282,
    "chapter": "XX. The Way",
    "themes": ["growth", "learning", "effort", "focus", "self-improvement"],
    "text": {
      "en": "From effort, wisdom grows; without it, wisdom fades. Knowing these two paths, place yourself where wisdom can increase.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 282",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 290,
    "chapter": "XXI. Miscellaneous",
    "themes": ["sacrifice", "perspective", "priorities", "wisdom", "long-term"],
    "text": {
      "en": "If by letting go of a small pleasure one finds a greater joy, let the wise release the small for the sake of the great.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 290",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 300,
    "chapter": "XXI. Miscellaneous",
    "themes": ["compassion", "kindness", "presence", "mindfulness", "peace"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The mindful are ever awake, their hearts by day and night delighting in compassion.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 300",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 301,
    "chapter": "XXI. Miscellaneous",
    "themes": ["meditation", "peace", "presence", "mindfulness", "stillness"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The mindful are ever awake, their hearts by day and night delighting in stillness.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 301",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 304,
    "chapter": "XXI. Miscellaneous",
    "themes": ["character", "integrity", "quiet-strength", "goodness", "authenticity"],
    "text": {
      "en": "The good shine from afar, like snow-capped mountains; the unworthy go unseen, like arrows shot into the night.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 304",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 224,
    "chapter": "XVII. Anger",
    "themes": ["truth", "patience", "generosity", "kindness", "character"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Speak the truth, do not give way to anger, give freely even when you have little — by these three, you draw near to the divine.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 224",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 291,
    "chapter": "XXI. Miscellaneous",
    "themes": ["conflict", "consequences", "kindness", "relationships", "letting-go"],
    "text": {
      "en": "One who seeks their own happiness by causing others pain becomes tangled in hatred and is never freed from it.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 291",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 12,
    "chapter": "I. The Twin-Verses",
    "themes": ["truth", "clarity", "discernment", "wisdom", "authenticity"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Those who see truth as truth and untruth as untruth arrive at what is real, following what truly matters.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 12",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 79,
    "chapter": "VI. The Wise Man",
    "themes": ["peace", "serenity", "joy", "contentment", "calm"],
    "text": {
      "en": "One who drinks deeply of wisdom lives happily, with a mind made serene.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 79",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 218,
    "chapter": "XVI. Pleasure",
    "themes": ["longing", "aspiration", "peace", "growth", "seeking"],
    "text": {
      "en": "One in whom a longing for the boundless has arisen, whose mind is content and unclouded by craving, is carried upward like a stream.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 218",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  },
  {
    "id": 293,
    "chapter": "XXI. Miscellaneous",
    "themes": ["mindfulness", "focus", "self-discipline", "peace", "intentional-living"],
    "text": {
      "en": "Those whose attention rests steadily on what they do, doing what should be done and leaving the rest, find their restless cravings come to an end.",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    },
    "citation": {
      "en": "Dhammapada, Verse 293",
      "hi": "",
      "zh": ""
    }
  }
]
